## VLANs and VPNs

### What is a LAN

A LAN is a local area network. It is just a bunch of devices in the same broadcast domain. So if you can imagine a subnet is a room, you can consider a LAN as kind of the building where your room is at, same as during the Azure relevant information section covered earlier. Now these devices can talk to one another because of a switch. A switch is like in those old buildings the pneumatic tube system each room is connected to so they can send stuff to each other and to themselves. They are in the same LAN and if you have different devices they can talk to each other.

### The Problem with Physical Networks

So if you want a different building or network you would need to have another one constructed so its another isolated instance of whatever devices you want. Now that is all fine and dandy but there is a teensy tiny problem: a huge number of switch ports are left unused. This is similar to the classful situation in the sense that people would end up getting too much for what they actually need.

Imagine that you do have a building complete with the tube system and the works. A few people are using the system just fine but that is the main issue, its only a few people and a huge amount of tubes are still being unused. You decided to construct another building to host a different set of people and still few of them are using it. At that rate you can say goodbye to your money because of the costs and maintenance.

### What is a VLAN

Never fear however, since we all made that mistake in our thinking process before. So how do we fully utilize the same tubing system while making sure that the rooms and objects who use it have privacy from each other?

Simple. This is what is called a VLAN or a Virtual Local Area Network. Instead of buying another building and tubing system upfront, we can instead use our current tubing system and apply privacy and segmentation, a fancy word for dividing stuff, at the logical not physical level. So if you go look on a switch you would see your own devices connected and what VLAN does is it can allot slots to a certain network so each batch of slots is technically a separate network.

### What is a VPN

You will have more or less some exposure to VPNs. In the Play or App Store they are called like NordVPN, Surfshark and etc. VPN means a Virtual Private Network. You would think that it is just used so you can watch stuff restricted by your region because providers like Netflix are jerks, am I right?

On a very very high level, what it does is it takes the data you give and receive through the internet through a private tunnel. And if someone with bad intentions would try to intercept that traffic they would not get any useful info, just scrambled jargon. It is like once a letter or data comes out of your building, instead of your regular post office guy an armored truck with a bunch of heavily armed dudes takes your letter, puts it in a sensitive case and sends it to the destination that you want. God forbid someone attacked that convoy, since its in a case if they access your letter inside all they would see is a bunch of random letters because the case needs to be decrypted before being readable.

A part of this is called a VPN concentrator, a networking appliance typically fitted in your firewall. It is like your own personal army delivering your messages in a secure manner. This is enterprise grade stuff though so you would be better off with 5 bucks a month from a subscription.

### How VPNs are Deployed

This is achieved through a mix of both hardware and software aspects like the concentrator mentioned above and there are also many types of how you can deploy your own VPNs. There are some purely hardware, some purely software and some that have a varying ratio between the two. But generally for some of them you do need to use them with your client software. NordVPN as an example we can consider as a software solution, so you need to use their software so you can have a VPN. This means regardless of where you connect, even if its not recommended, you can still have a layer of security. For example accessing an open WiFi network, although still very unsecure.

### Trunking

Now when we are trying to connect other networks with VLANs through their switches, if we configure it correctly we can simply just take ethernet cables that correspond to each other's VLANs. Like for example, I have VLAN one on 4 ports and on the other switch I also have 4 ports. I can connect those two and they will be able to talk normally. Sounds simple right? Because in small settings you can get away with it.

Now I want you to imagine linking 100 or 1000 VLANs. The switches do not have enough ports and you also do not have enough cables either. By the time you even finish crimping each and every one you would have seen man go to the Moon a second time already. That is why trunking exists.

A VLAN trunk basically is a one stop shop for your switch so it can send and receive data from multiple VLANs all in one cable. This is also referred to as **802.1Q VLAN trunking**. This is only applicable to physical settings but the concepts still need to be understood because in the next section on network segmentation you will understand the necessary logic to how to provision your limited network resources. So the trunking process itself might not help you much in your Azure journey but its underlying principles definitely will.

To speed things up, it is like you are sending a letter to the post guy and you have a stamp on it. The post guy knows which block or district it belongs to even if he is carrying a bunch of other letters with multiple different stamps. But when your receiver finally gets your letter they get rid of the stamp you put on because it only serves to identify where you want your letter to go.

