## Network Segmentation

I honestly was bracing myself for another thesis dissertation on this topic but I am frankly disappointed on how easy the principle is. I am going to explain it to you. There are a number of reasons why network segmentation exists. For the sake of actually explaining something of worth to your learning I will at the very least go a little bit in depth when it comes to each of the use cases.

### Security

This is the most obvious one. We segment networks on the basis of this logic: we do not want neighbors snooping around and finding our personal problems basically. We do not want to look at other neighbors' stuff either and if something bad happens to them that same bad thing will not happen to us. Especially when sensitive information like credit cards are involved, they do need to be segmented so customers and bad actors cannot reach them that easily.

### Efficiency

It goes back to how you will use Azure to properly provision your subnets. If you are able to give just enough resources to either a device or a service, ironically they would work better than having too much or too little. It also helps to bear in mind that resources are money. Network segmentation helps us to be more efficient by allowing the possibilities of spreading our resources wherever we need them instead of just buying another and another. That is a bad mindset to have as a future cloud engineer.

### Compliance

This one is the least interesting of the three but you do need to understand why certain rules are in place for a reason. Like for example in the nuclear research industry, they always have strict compliance measures for limiting radiation exposure by time, distance and shielding. As the saying goes, regulations are written in someone else's blood. Some industries and devices need to be properly segmented because they are critical infrastructure or life saving machines. Those devices need to have their own stable, secure and properly isolated bubble to keep our society running.

And all three are important for you to bear in mind whenever we progress on our journey, because its not a job to be a cloud engineer. It is a hard earned privilege and responsibility especially if you are working in critical infrastructure.

