## Microsoft Learn Section: Configure Virtual Networks

For this section specifically we are going to focus on the main Learn sandbox stuff for the AZ-104. I might have a separate README that overviews what I did for this entire section but here gives me a bit more room to go over what I did on the Microsoft Learn stuff. Admittedly there might be a lot of hand holding but what is important is that you recognize what is going on and if you do not you always ask and then try again.

The lab activity we are going to work through is from the Configure Virtual Networks module on the AZ-104. The structure will be based on subsections laid out below and from here on out it will be my synthesis of the entire module to make it understandable for both of us.

### Introduction

Remember our metaphors, the one where we consider our network a building? The things that we are going to talk about involve virtual networks so similar to VLANs they are networks but they are like that in a logical sense. It is mostly software defined stuff but admittedly they can and do have real connectivity but within private networks. So if you connect your stuff to Azure it is with a VPN or ExpressRoute if your company is loaded. VNets are mainly for securing communications with their resources, also scalability and availability. Scalability means that if you need more of a said resource you can expand current capacity or acquire more instances of that resource to accommodate your needs. Availability means even if hell freezes over, your services and operations are still running no matter what.

### Plan Virtual Networks

Earlier I mentioned things about network segmentation and why the concept exists in the first place. Those principles perfectly apply to how we want to plan our networks here. Planning makes sure you do not over or under allocate addresses within your virtual network. It totally depends on your use cases whether you are just planning a small scale project or a huge cloud server. You can either:

Create a dedicated private cloud only virtual network, which is a fancy way of saying you can literally prop up a cloud server. Or securely extend your data center with virtual networks, so if you want to connect your on premises stuff to the cloud you can do it but for the sole reason to extend capacity. Or enable hybrid cloud scenarios which is just the same as the second point but your intent is to facilitate certain stuff on premises and then in the cloud.

To tie back to our metaphors, this is how Azure as a construction company wants to give you the opportunity to have your own personal building somewhere far away. They are in charge of everything except what is the layout of the building, the rooms sectioned off, the objects within those rooms and how the floor plan is structured. That part is on you.

### Create Subnets

I have already talked about the stuff you would mostly need in the previous sections however I do want to add a few key considerations.

You should consider service requirements. Every resource has their own network requirements in the building created by Azure and the types of data coming and going from these services. A service like Azure Firewall will definitely need its own dedicated subnet so it can function properly.

Consider your network virtual appliances. As we go over more advanced stuff within this guide we have to consider that Azure naturally routes network traffic between all subnets in a network. That is a huge issue when it comes to security but we can override the settings wherever it applies accordingly.

Consider also your network security groups because they act as your firewalls, allowing or not allowing certain IP ranges and whatnot.

### Create Virtual Networks

These are pretty straightforward. Here is what Microsoft Learn says about creating a virtual network and I am wrapping it in plain language so you know what each point actually means:

```
When you create a virtual network, you need to define the IP address space for the network.

Plan to use an IP address space that is not already in use in your organization.

The address space for the virtual network can be either on-premises or in the cloud, but not both.

To create a virtual network, you need to define at least one subnet.

Each subnet contains a range of IP addresses that fall within the virtual network address space.

The address range for each subnet must be unique within the address space for the virtual network.

The range for one subnet cannot overlap with other subnet IP address ranges in the same virtual network.

You can create a virtual network in the Azure portal by providing the Azure subscription, resource group,
virtual network name, and service region for the network.
```

This is essentially a literal how-to on how you can build your own building in the cloud. It tells you how many ID cards you will need, how you would enforce the tubing system and etc. The reason why you need to put unique subnet ranges is the exact same logic why you cannot cut the same pie twice in the same place. The original piece is already gone.

The last thing I can tell you is that your subnetting knowledge will help you in this section specifically. If you are a visual thinker like me the switches analogy will go a long way, and the power of twos as well, because when you are working on the portal directly a lot of information is provided like how many available IPs are in each subnet respectively.

### Plan IP Addressing

We are going to use our ID card idea for this. You want to place a private ID card or IP address onto your objects or services and devices if it means managing your stuff within your virtual network. However if you have public facing services like hosting a website you should get a public IPv4 address, its cheap anyway.

Usually you can just use dynamic addressing to solve most of your problems but for the sake of getting your experience in and making sure you have a bit of muscle memory I recommend going manual at least for now. Especially when we are making our networks with NSGs where they will always base rules on the IP ranges you dish out.

Also for my own personal context as of the time of this writing, it is important in a sense where I would need DNS services or if my budget allows a personal domain I can keep up for cheap where I can host the web app we have.

### Create Public IP Addressing

Through the Azure portal you can create your own public IP address for a resource you have. You would need one for public facing services like in my case the website where I will host the web app for our resource. There are a few things to keep in mind though.

IPv4 and IPv6 public IPs are available and the SKU and tier of the IP address you have must match the same respectively of the load balancer you are using. When you are given an IP address they are mostly static. It is like for another object that connects your room to the outside world, it must match the tier of your ID card and the batch number your ID card was made.

> Note: Always verify current public IP pricing directly on the Azure pricing page before provisioning as Microsoft updated their public IP pricing in 2023. Costs may be higher than expected especially for IPs attached to running resources.

### Associate Public IP Addresses

For some resources in Azure not only do you have to create these public IPs properly but you also have to make sure that you are aware of how these are respectively associated with each other. This is exactly why I prefer that you study a bit about AZ-900 content because I made this guide knowing specifically that I already passed it. It is a really good exam and study to help you understand what the cloud is. But for scoping purposes I will just stick to networking fundamentals and how they reflect in Azure. Most of these are services you will encounter properly in the AZ-104 content. For now just know that each type of resource associates its public IP differently.

Here is a simple reference chart from Microsoft Learn:

```
Resource                                                            Association
Virtual machine                                                     Network interface configuration
Virtual Network Gateway (VPN), Virtual Network Gateway (ER),
NAT Gateway                                                         Gateway IP configuration
Public Load Balancer, Application Gateway, Azure Firewall,
Route Server, API Management                                        Front-end configuration
Bastion host                                                        Public IP configuration
```

Most of these terms are content covered within AZ-900. Now that I think and reflect on it, it is an eye opening experience that if I wanted to teach you the reader anything Azure relevant you must know what I am talking about. It is a long long term goal but maybe one day I would also like to make an AZ-900 version of this guide. But yeah, onward and upward.

### Allocate or Assign Private IP Addresses

A private IP is like an ID card that can only be used within a specific building. And like the last section here is another reference chart for associating these kinds of addresses:

```
Resource                  Association                   Dynamic    Static
Virtual machine           NIC                           Yes        Yes
Internal load balancer    Front-end configuration       Yes        Yes
Application gateway       Front-end configuration       Yes        Yes
```

Remember our IPv4 addressing? The same stuff that applies there applies here too. You can use both dynamic and static addressing. A key trick that I can tell you later is that once we get into the specifics of NSGs you can use them to make sure that an entire subnet is successfully isolated from the rest. And you can use the subnetting we have been talking about to only allocate for the resources you need, making your network compact and efficient. But bear in mind when configuring your main VNet, always have a lot of addresses on standby.

Dynamic just lets Azure pick from the addresses available in your subnet and static means you will have to do it yourself.

And that is pretty much it for the thought process I have for this topic. On the summary README I will go over in more detail about the lab work but for here at least it is enough to get you oriented.

